                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d327">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">837.515/583: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Braden</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Habana</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-07-09T15:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 9, 1942—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 4:38 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>528. Department’s telegram No. 418 of July 2 [<hi rend="italic">3</hi>],
                    midnight. Ministry of Finance inquires whether arrangements could be made to
                    deliver to local branch of any American bank which our Treasury may designate
                    the United States currency required to pay for the first $5,000,000 of gold to
                    be purchased provided the Treasury feels that additional United States currency
                    is needed here for sugar loan and for expenses the several United States
                    Government defense projects now being executed. Ministry of Finance officials
                    point out that this procedure would save remittance charges both ways.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Braden</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
